PSL1GHT runtime: switch startfile asm + sprx OPD descriptors + lv2.ld
to ELF64 + ILP32 + compact 8-byte OPD.

The hand-written PSL1GHT startfiles (crt0.S, lv2-crti.S, lv2-crtn.S)
and the sprx export-trampoline macro (sprx/common/exports.S) targeted
the legacy LP64 + 24-byte ELFv1 ABI:

  - 64-bit address loads via the 5-instruction li/oris/sldi/oris/ori
    sequence;
  - 8-byte stack/LR/TOC saves via std/stdu/ld;
  - .opd descriptors emitted as `.quad ea, .TOC.@tocbase, 0` (24 bytes
    per entry, 8-byte fields, R_PPC64_TOC reloc on the toc field);
  - the linker script forced .opd / .got to ALIGN(8).

Under the ELF64 + ILP32 hybrid ABI:

  - addresses fit in 32 bits; a single lis/addi pair replaces the
    5-instruction LOAD_DWORD;
  - stack/LR/TOC live in 4 bytes — std → stw, ld → lwz, stdu → stwu;
  - .opd descriptors are 8-byte compact: `.long ea, .TOC.` (4-byte
    R_PPC64_ADDR32 each, no env field), matching what GCC's own
    crtbegin/crtend emit;
  - the .opd section alignment drops to ALIGN(4), and .got gets the
    same treatment so an 8-byte alignment cannot be force-induced
    that would mislead post-link tooling into treating the section
    as ELFv1.

ENTRY(_start) in lv2.ld must resolve to a function-descriptor-shape
symbol, so _start (no leading dot) is now defined alongside __start
on the same compact 8-byte slot.

Without these changes, every binary linked through the PSL1GHT crt
ends up with a mixed .opd (LP64-shape entries from the crt + compact
entries from C/C++ TUs); a compact-aware caller doing
`lwz r2,4(rOPD)` reads either zero (jumps to NULL) or the high 4
bytes of an 8-byte ea (a 64-bit-shaped value that segfaults outside
user space).

